            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">Ḥēdra is a small town situated in the northwest of the Kasserine Governorate, just a few kilometres from the Algerian border. With an altitude of 810 m, it is one of the highest towns of Tunisia.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">The ruins of the antique Roman city Ammaedara are situated close to the modern town. It is one of the oldest archaeological sites of Romans in Africa, established at the beginning of the Roman Empire. In 30 BC, a Roman army settled here and built its first fortress. Before the Romans, the Numidians and Carthaginians occupied the territory. Its location was of strategic importance for the Romans, as it was situated on the road between Carthage and Theveste (the modern Tébessa in Algeria). The archeological site of Haidra shows the remains of one of the largest Byzantine fortresses in the Maghreb. It used to be a diocese and is now a Roman Catholic titular see. A small museum exhibits interesting mosaics.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">In modern times, Haidra witnessed a quick development as meeting point of roads. In the 17<sup>th</sup> and 18<sup>th</sup> century, it was only a small village, with some neighbouring settlements. French colonial powers built a railway station in Haidra in 1934 to transport goods like wood and phosphate. </p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Some of the villages in its surrounding are Ain Difla, Mkimen, Mrira, and Gargara. The climate is semi-arid, with hot summers up to 41 degrees and cold winters. It can even snow from time to time – which makes the archeological site even more attractive to visitors.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve">To the best of our knowledge hitherto no research has been done on the dialect of Haidra. However, this dialect is linguistically investigated within the TUNOCENT project.</p>
            </div>
